  whatItMeans: {
    en: "Public Health Law 4201 is the New York chain-of-command statute for disposition of human remains. It governs who decides whether the body is buried or cremated, where, and how. The statutory priority list (PHL 4201(2)) runs in descending order: (1) a person 18 or older designated in a written instrument signed by the decedent and meeting the statute's form; (2) the decedent's surviving spouse; (2-a) the decedent's surviving domestic partner; (3) any surviving child 18 or older; (4) either surviving parent; (5) any surviving sibling 18 or older; (6) a guardian appointed under SCPA Article 17 or 17-A or Mental Hygiene Law Article 81; (7) any person 18 or older who would be entitled to a share in the estate as a distributee under EPTL 4-1.1; (8) a duly appointed fiduciary of the estate; (9) any close friend or relative 18 or older who is willing to assume responsibility; (10) a public administrator of the county. Written designation (the safest path): a decedent can name any adult individual to control disposition by signing a written instrument substantially in the form prescribed by PHL 4201(3). The form states the designee's name, contact information, and any specific instructions. Two witnesses 18 or older must sign. A copy should be given to the designee and kept with other estate planning documents — the original is best kept with the will or in a place the family can access quickly. The designation overrides all family preferences, including a spouse's. Disqualification (PHL 4201(7)): a surviving spouse loses priority if (a) a divorce action was pending when the decedent died, with final judgment of divorce or annulment or separation to be expected, or (b) the spouse had abandoned the decedent. Similarly, any person who has been convicted of committing a felony against the decedent is disqualified. Multiple members of the same tier: if two or more people share the top available priority (for example, three adult children), the disposition is determined by a majority of the tier members who are reasonably available. If the tier is evenly split and no designation exists, any tier member may petition Supreme Court for a determining order. Court resolution: PHL 4201(4) gives courts authority to resolve disputes about disposition. A higher-priority person who is unwilling, incapacitated, or unavailable can be bypassed; a lower-priority person can seek an order. Unresolved disputes are handled on an expedited basis because of refrigeration and statutory time pressure. Funeral director's role: licensed funeral directors (regulated by NYS Bureau of Funeral Directing, 10 NYCRR Part 77) must follow the PHL 4201 priority list. A director who proceeds on the direction of a lower-priority person over a known higher-priority person faces license discipline and civil liability. A director will typically require photo ID, proof of relationship (birth or marriage certificate in some cases), and a signed authorization. If the director knows of a dispute, the director will hold the remains until resolution. Cremation authorization: New York requires a written cremation authorization signed by the person with disposition right (10 NYCRR 77.7). The cremator cannot proceed without it. If the top-priority person cannot be located, the director will require a court order. Burial vs. cremation: the decedent's own wishes, if known, are persuasive evidence in any dispute but do not legally bind the authorized decision-maker unless captured in a signed PHL 4201(3) designation or similar prepaid funeral contract. Anatomical gift (organ and body donation): Public Health Law Article 43 governs. A decedent's own signed gift is binding; next-of-kin consent applies only when the decedent made no gift. Donor Registry enrollment overrides family objection in most cases. Prepaid funeral trusts and contracts: a prepaid funeral trust under General Business Law Article 42 names a funeral home and usually specifies burial/cremation and location. The trust binds the funeral home on the prepaid services, but does not override PHL 4201 on authority — the statutory decision-maker still signs. Cost consideration: in a contested or delayed situation, storage and refrigeration fees accrue to the estate. Resolution delays of more than 7-10 days can add thousands of dollars in charges. Crematoria and cemeteries typically bill the estate. Multi-state concerns: if a decedent dies outside New York but is to be buried or cremated in New York, the state of death's chain-of-command law governs the initial release. Once in New York, PHL 4201 governs final disposition."
  },

